00:20:04,960 --> 00:20:05,960
Thank you. Joe?

175
00:20:07,180 --> 00:20:14,480
Speaking of Gladiator 2, I haven't seen it, but somebody said something to me about Gladiator 2.

176
00:20:14,480 --> 00:20:18,400
It was one of the most insane comments I've ever heard a person say about a movie.

177
00:20:19,260 --> 00:20:24,540
And it was insane because I was like, that's what I would have said 10 years ago about a movie.

178
00:20:24,540 --> 00:20:27,740
And I get now why people looked at me like I was crazy.

179
00:20:28,800 --> 00:20:36,260
But my friend Becky, and she's obsessed with Gladiator 1, and Hans Zimmer, I believe, did the score for Gladiator 1.

180
00:20:36,500 --> 00:20:42,100
And she said, I can't believe he didn't do the score for Gladiator 2.

181
00:20:42,160 --> 00:20:45,500
They ruined that movie by not having him do the score.

182
00:20:45,820 --> 00:20:47,940
And I said, oh, I haven't seen it.

183
00:20:48,400 --> 00:20:50,740
And she goes, I didn't see it.

184
00:20:50,760 --> 00:20:54,800
I was like, well, it's a crazy statement to make.

185
00:20:54,820 --> 00:20:57,560
And then she started laughing like, I know that sounds insane.

186
00:20:57,580 --> 00:21:01,140
I was like, all right, yeah. But I was like, I would have said that same thing 10 years ago.

187
00:21:01,320 --> 00:21:03,620
I hate it. Have you seen it? No.

188
00:21:04,760 --> 00:21:07,820
I feel like we've had that conversation many times on this show.

189
00:21:09,120 --> 00:21:13,420
Gladiator 2, I think you and I were maybe going to do, so I never discussed it.

190
00:21:13,420 --> 00:21:17,380
But if you were curious about what my thoughts on it were, it wasn't very good.

191
00:21:18,840 --> 00:21:23,180
I love Denzel in it. And I think Paul Mascall is the best actor of his generation.

192
00:21:23,180 --> 00:21:27,020
He was completely miscast and should not have been playing that part.

193
00:21:28,660 --> 00:21:34,560
And there's no, I mean, Crowe dies in the first one, but there's no Crowe cameo like in a flashback or something?

194
00:21:35,140 --> 00:21:39,880
No Crowe cameo. And I know he was very offended that they didn't reach out to him.

195
00:21:39,880 --> 00:21:46,960
And then they asked Ridley Scott, hey, so like, you know, Russell Crowe was kind of bothered that he wasn't asked.

196
00:21:47,380 --> 00:21:51,300
Why would he have been asked? He was so dismissive of him.

197
00:21:51,380 --> 00:21:54,020
He was like, why would we have called him? What are you talking about?

198
00:21:54,820 --> 00:21:57,160
Ridley, even if you feel that way, that's crazy.

199
00:21:57,520 --> 00:22:03,080
Did you see the interview with Crowe where he's like, you know, he was like, I was in Greece.

200
00:22:04,100 --> 00:22:08,840
I looked from a hotel balcony across the water at an island.

201
00:22:10,200 --> 00:22:16,300
It's all kinds of fanfare going on. I didn't know what it was.

202
00:22:16,300 --> 00:22:19,680
Turns out they were shooting Gladiator 2. I didn't even know they were making it.

203
00:22:19,760 --> 00:22:23,520
And the guy's like, you didn't know they were making it? Like, are you in it?

204
00:22:23,520 --> 00:22:25,620
And he's like, who gives a fuck?

205
00:22:27,440 --> 00:22:32,660
So just classic Russell Crowe, like, just like, get out of my face, idiot.

206
00:22:33,440 --> 00:22:39,000
There's no amount of age or wisdom that can keep you from being just a jealous little bitch.

207
00:22:39,040 --> 00:22:40,940
Sometimes I do it all the time.

208
00:22:42,900 --> 00:22:48,140
I do like Russell Crowe. He was so exciting when he came on the scene.

209
00:22:48,680 --> 00:22:53,660
You remember that time, LA Confidential into Gladiator, it was like, holy shit, this guy.

210
00:22:54,160 --> 00:23:01,880
Yeah, he was one of those guys where they were like, he's going to be our next De Niro or Bogart, whoever they made the comparisons to.

211
00:23:03,080 --> 00:23:07,660
But I got to say, I think I prefer, this might be my favorite era of Crowe.

212
00:23:07,660 --> 00:23:13,880
Like, I love fat drunk. Give me the paycheck. I'll play a priest again.

213
00:23:14,900 --> 00:23:24,600
He was such a sex symbol that I never would have dreamed that he was going to become our Orson Welles, which is basically what he is.

214
00:23:25,280 --> 00:23:29,880
Playing fat priest after fat priest. I'm into it, too.

215
00:23:29,920 --> 00:23:35,940
I do hope he gets out of this direct to DVD ghetto at some point, but I'm a big fan.

216
00:23:35,940 --> 00:23:42,340
Let's go to the corner, if we could. I only have two today.

217
00:23:45,780 --> 00:23:46,340
Oh, you want me to go?

218
00:23:46,980 --> 00:23:52,460
I was going to say, I don't have much of a theme here. You can go first. I don't care.

219
00:23:53,060 --> 00:24:03,780
Very well. I watched a couple Preston Sturges movies. Sturges did Sullivan's Travels and a lot in The Criterion Collection, Palm Beach Story.

220
00:24:03,780 --> 00:24:09,620
I considered one of the pioneers, one of the greats, the experts of the screwball comedy.

221
00:24:10,300 --> 00:24:16,780
And I have a box set of his that, like a lot of my box sets, I had never opened in 25 years.

222
00:24:17,420 --> 00:24:20,380
I popped it open. I was like, I want to see everything this guy's done.

223
00:24:21,260 --> 00:24:25,880
And I watched a couple of really charming early movies of his. One is The Great McGinty.

224
00:24:27,640 --> 00:24:35,180
He wrote the screenplay. He went into the studio. He said, you can pay me $1 for this screenplay if you let me direct it.

225
00:24:35,440 --> 00:24:42,440
And they did. And very much the Rocky thing, just like the only way you're going to make this movie is if you let me direct it.

226
00:24:42,440 --> 00:24:46,780
They ultimately did not let Stallone direct that movie, but they did let Preston Sturges.

227
00:24:47,380 --> 00:24:52,860
And it's great. It got nominated for an Oscar for Best Screenplay and led to great success for him.

228
00:24:52,860 --> 00:24:56,680
And I always loved those stories of somebody taking a chance on him or herself.

229
00:24:58,920 --> 00:25:07,520
It's really funny. 82 minutes, lightning fast screwball comedy dialogue, character actors out the ass.

230
00:25:07,620 --> 00:25:15,020
I love these old black and white movies, all the old like, you scoundrel, you scallywag.

231
00:25:15,180 --> 00:25:18,900
That's always fun watching that shit. It's a very funny movie.

232
00:25:18,900 --> 00:25:26,100
Basically, it's a guy who helps, and it was timely.

233
00:25:26,460 --> 00:25:32,420
He gets hired by a politician to go out and vote falsely, vote for him.

234
00:25:32,980 --> 00:25:38,080
And he says, I'll pay you $10 if you go do this. And he does it 37 times.

235
00:25:38,140 --> 00:25:40,940
He votes falsely 37 times, so he gets a big check.

236
00:25:42,120 --> 00:25:47,060
And he's such a likable guy that they wind up putting, you know, it's the classic Capra thing.

237
00:25:47,060 --> 00:25:51,800
He becomes a politician himself, and he's like, yeah, I'll just keep being a scumbag.

238
00:25:52,020 --> 00:25:58,600
And then he winds up, they pair him up with a woman because no politician can be successful without a wife by his side.

239
00:25:59,120 --> 00:26:03,840
And his fake wife starts being like, I think you can do better.

240
00:26:04,080 --> 00:26:06,860
You know, I don't think you got to be a piece of shit to be a politician.

241
00:26:06,860 --> 00:26:13,320
So, you know, it's a little, it's a little corny, a little kind of like that.

242
00:26:13,860 --> 00:26:21,180
We can even the common man can make a difference type movie, which is very much Preston Sturges, very much Frank Capra.

243
00:26:21,380 --> 00:26:26,220
And it's a little corny in spots, but overall very funny old classic screwball comedy. Joe?

244
00:26:26,580 --> 00:26:36,080
I rewatched all of the because I bought that Dirty Harry DVD set, the collectible one that I lucked out and got brand new at a half price books for $20.

245
00:26:36,860 --> 00:26:44,120
But I rewatched all the Dirty Harry movies. I already talked about the first one.

246
00:26:45,320 --> 00:26:51,860
The only sequel that I really think is worthwhile is the third movie, which is The Enforcer.

247
00:26:53,280 --> 00:26:57,460
That's the one with Tyne Daly where she becomes the second one.

248
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:00,680
No, Magnum Force is the second one.

249
00:27:01,440 --> 00:27:09,720
Magnum Force has the best intro because it's the camera zooming in on his hand, holding the Magnum.

250
00:27:10,080 --> 00:27:14,800
Right. On like a, you know, blank background, whatever.

251
00:27:16,600 --> 00:27:20,140
And he's doing a monologue about the force of the gun.

252
00:27:20,620 --> 00:27:25,320
Like it's a great intro, but then the movie doesn't really deliver after that.

253
00:27:26,300 --> 00:27:28,720
But The Enforcer is a good one.

254
00:27:29,760 --> 00:27:32,640
And it's the logical sequel to the first one.

255
00:27:34,140 --> 00:27:38,040
You know, he's pissed off in the first movie about getting a new partner.

256
00:27:39,280 --> 00:27:45,460
There are some racial aspects to why he's aggravated about it.

257
00:27:46,420 --> 00:27:49,380
That they play more for comedy than him being truly upset.

258
00:27:49,680 --> 00:27:53,460
In the third movie, he's teamed up with a woman.

259
00:27:54,300 --> 00:28:02,100
And it's because there's a almost DEI style movement happening in the police force.

260
00:28:02,800 --> 00:28:08,920
Where they want to get more women on the street and he's pissed off about it because he's like, it's not about representation.

261
00:28:09,020 --> 00:28:11,500
It's about, are you a good cop or not?

262
00:28:12,240 --> 00:28:18,620
He gets paired up with Tyne Daly because his chief is spitefully doing so.

263
00:28:19,800 --> 00:28:23,100
And he grows to really care about her.

264
00:28:23,340 --> 00:28:26,360
And she is a great cop and it shows that he was wrong.

265
00:28:27,120 --> 00:28:34,840
Which makes, spoiler alert, when she's killed at the end, an amazing moment in the movie.

266
00:28:35,300 --> 00:28:41,920
It's heartbreaking. And you see a human side of Harry that you don't often get to see in these movies.

267
00:28:43,940 --> 00:28:45,840
I forget who plays the villain in The Enforcer.

268
00:28:45,840 --> 00:28:48,180
I'm going to look it up really quick.

269
00:28:48,720 --> 00:28:53,000
I rewatched all five of those over the pandemic and I thought they were all pretty good.

270
00:28:55,440 --> 00:29:01,140
I didn't, I think Bobby, or D. Varen Bookwalter, that's who it is.

271
00:29:01,160 --> 00:29:04,200
He plays the killer and the killer in this one is a sniper.

272
00:29:05,140 --> 00:29:07,020
He's killing people from a distance.

273
00:29:09,800 --> 00:29:12,960
I disagree, I just, I couldn't.

274
00:29:12,960 --> 00:29:17,780
The second one was like a sort of watered down revisit to me.

275
00:29:18,880 --> 00:29:25,420
This third one got back into the themes that are challenging about the first one.

276
00:29:27,120 --> 00:29:31,960
And it just had the grit and it just felt like a sequel to me.

277
00:29:32,220 --> 00:29:38,700
The other ones, The Deadpool, Sudden Impact, and Magnum Force.

278
00:29:39,360 --> 00:29:46,080
They just feel way more to me like it's Clint Eastwood playing a cop, but not necessarily Dirty Harry.

279
00:29:46,160 --> 00:29:50,180
This felt like Dirty Harry to me. I really enjoyed it.

280
00:29:50,300 --> 00:29:56,040
It made me sad that Gran Torino is not an official Dirty Harry sequel.

281
00:29:56,280 --> 00:30:00,820
Because I was like, if that was the third official movie, that would be a perfect trilogy to me.

282
00:30:01,120 --> 00:30:05,360
But then I actually read up again on Gran Torino.

283
00:30:05,360 --> 00:30:13,500
And it was interesting because I found a lot of reviews that said this is not just a spiritual sequel enclosure to Dirty Harry.

284
00:30:13,920 --> 00:30:21,100
It's also the closure to his stranger characters in all those westerns he played, or did.

285
00:30:22,060 --> 00:30:25,860
He's the man against the town, you know, dealing with the threat.

286
00:30:25,880 --> 00:30:28,120
And I was like, oh shit, I never thought of it like that.

287
00:30:28,820 --> 00:30:34,720
So I think Gran Torino kind of serves as a closing piece to a lot of things that Eastwood did.

288
00:30:36,360 --> 00:30:43,360
But I enjoyed The Enforcer. I thought it had more depth in a character sense than any of the other sequels.

289
00:30:44,560 --> 00:30:50,040
And it's a fun watch, man. It's a good movie. It's a good entry.

290
00:30:51,320 --> 00:30:58,120
I would recommend The Rookie as a movie that should have been a Dirty Harry and was considered to be a Dirty Harry.

291
00:30:58,320 --> 00:31:03,080
But it's him and Charlie Sheen. Raul Julia is the villain.

292
00:31:03,080 --> 00:31:05,960
Co -written by the guy who did Evil Dead 2.

293
00:31:06,960 --> 00:31:15,760
Lots of really crazy set pieces in it. I really like The Rookie, which was really unfairly hated because I think it's as good as all the Dirty Harry sequels.

294
00:31:17,740 --> 00:31:21,800
I watched another Preston Sturges, which was called Christmas in July.

295
00:31:22,820 --> 00:31:31,840
This movie was 67 minutes long, ladies and gentlemen, and it told a coherent story and a romance, and it was very funny.

296
00:31:31,840 --> 00:31:39,880
So I'm not sure why everything needs to be 230 these days, but I like this even more than The Great McGinty.

297
00:31:39,920 --> 00:31:44,400
This was about an actor who I normally don't give a shit about, Dick Powell.

298
00:31:46,480 --> 00:31:53,720
He plays an office clerk who enters all kinds of contests, very similar to Punch Drunk Love with the pudding points.

299
00:31:53,760 --> 00:31:56,320
He's just a guy who loves entering contests.

300
00:31:57,240 --> 00:32:08,460
He enters one where he's got to make up a slogan for a coffee company, and he makes this slogan that makes no sense, and everyone in his life tells him it makes no sense.

301
00:32:09,560 --> 00:32:13,140
But his co -workers lie and tell him that he won.

302
00:32:14,060 --> 00:32:23,700
And the theme of the movie is basically like, if you think you've got some money, and if you act like you've got some money, everyone will treat you as such and treat you with respect.

303
00:32:25,240 --> 00:32:36,320
Great little theme, great little story, really, really funny movie with some funny performances, particularly this guy Raymond Walburn, who's been in a million old movies.

304
00:32:37,620 --> 00:32:44,180
The Coen Brothers try to do this a lot with their screwball comedies, like just give you a lot of really funny, goofy characters in the background.

305
00:32:45,600 --> 00:32:51,520
This Raymond Walburn stole the movie and is one of the funnier supporting performances I've ever seen in an old movie.

306
00:32:52,480 --> 00:33:04,260
Sturges is great, a 67 -minute effective, hilarious comedy. You've got to really admire that, and it's 85 years old, so pretty fucking impressive.

307
00:33:04,320 --> 00:33:04,680
Joe?

308
00:33:06,500 --> 00:33:15,120
I guess my theme is movies about men that portray men in a way that men aren't often portrayed anymore.

309
00:33:18,240 --> 00:33:24,540
Men that I'm sure a lot of modern women, these are movies they would cite as the problems with machismo.

310
00:33:25,640 --> 00:33:34,920
And not to say there aren't problems with machismo, but these characters are a hell of a lot of fun to watch in a movie, even though they might be nightmares to deal with in real life.

311
00:33:35,640 --> 00:33:38,480
But Tin Men, which is a movie I'd heard about.

312
00:33:38,480 --> 00:33:39,300
Oh yeah, funny movie.

313
00:33:39,800 --> 00:33:43,880
Oh, it's so funny, man. Barry Levinson directed it.

314
00:33:43,980 --> 00:33:53,600
I had originally, the reason I watched it was because after I watched Get Shorty, it came up as a suggested title.

315
00:33:55,300 --> 00:34:01,520
And I got confused. I thought for a second Barry Levinson directed Get Shorty, but that's Barry Sonnenfeld.

316
00:34:03,420 --> 00:34:07,620
It was a great autobiography, by the way, with really funny stories about his time in Hollywood.

317
00:34:09,780 --> 00:34:12,960
Nice. Levinson has directed a lot of great movies.

318
00:34:13,500 --> 00:34:17,000
Did the Alto Nights with Robert De Niro in a dual role.

319
00:34:17,920 --> 00:34:27,300
You know, I'm so bummed about that, man. It's like, if he didn't have that harebrained idea to cast De Niro in the dual role.

320
00:34:27,340 --> 00:34:33,740
If that was De Niro in Pesci, you would have seen that trailer. You would have been like, I gotta go see this. This is fucking awesome.

321
00:34:33,740 --> 00:34:38,800
And instead you're like, what is going on with this? I don't understand.

322
00:34:41,540 --> 00:34:49,180
Anyway, Barry Levinson directed Tin Men. It stars Richard Dreyfuss and Danny DeVito and Barbara Hershey.

323
00:34:49,820 --> 00:34:55,040
All of them excellent. But he also wrote this.

324
00:34:56,020 --> 00:34:59,180
It takes place in 1963 in Baltimore, Maryland.

325
00:35:00,440 --> 00:35:08,240
DeVito and Dreyfuss play tin salesmen who are technically competitors because they work at different companies.

326
00:35:09,060 --> 00:35:14,940
And the movie is about their feud. But the feud is not over. This is such a weird premise.

327
00:35:15,460 --> 00:35:21,360
They're not feuding because of the tin sales, the aluminum siding sales. That's what they do.

328
00:35:21,980 --> 00:35:25,220
They're feuding because they get into a car accident in the beginning.

329
00:35:26,460 --> 00:35:34,820
They both think it's the other guy's fault. And they're both such psychos. They're determined to get revenge on the other guy.

330
00:35:35,440 --> 00:35:38,660
And it just so happens they work in the same industry as competitors.

331
00:35:38,720 --> 00:35:46,480
But that never really comes into it outside of the fact that they're dealing with the same plight in their industry,

332
00:35:46,480 --> 00:35:53,800
which is this federal investigation about basically fraudulent sales of aluminum siding.

333
00:35:53,860 --> 00:35:55,540
That really happened. That was a real thing.

334
00:35:56,520 --> 00:36:04,240
Anyway, it's everything you want out of DeVito and Dreyfuss in a movie.

335
00:36:05,800 --> 00:36:14,100
Dreyfuss is playing an unhinged, just manic lunatic in this movie.

336
00:36:14,100 --> 00:36:19,400
And DeVito is playing a charming nut job.

337
00:36:20,360 --> 00:36:25,400
It's Dreyfuss freaking out and having meltdowns in every scene.

338
00:36:26,260 --> 00:36:35,160
And it's DeVito being explosive. It's what you want out of both of these guys as actors.

339
00:36:35,160 --> 00:36:44,540
It is so funny. And it has a tremendous amount of heart and takes a really nice dramatic turn in the third act.

340
00:36:45,540 --> 00:36:51,400
I immediately, I couldn't stop talking about it. I watched it once and I was like, I talked about it for days.

341
00:36:53,480 --> 00:36:59,540
Days and days. Patton Oswalt, not to name drop, but Patton Oswalt and I text a lot about movies.

342
00:37:00,660 --> 00:37:05,960
And I texted him and I was like, have you seen Tin Men, dude? I never saw it. I'm obsessed with it.

343
00:37:06,580 --> 00:37:14,040
He's like, I love that movie. And started immediately, this is what's fun about texting about movies, he'll start sending you all these facts about the movie.

344
00:37:14,400 --> 00:37:23,760
Like you can't stump him on anything. And it was just cool. And then I texted you about it as well and you're like, I love that movie.

345
00:37:24,620 --> 00:37:25,220
And I was like, okay.

346
00:37:25,220 --> 00:37:26,320
Mahoney by the way.

347
00:37:26,780 --> 00:37:42,320
Oh yeah, that's right. Mahoney by the way, playing a very charming, endearing guy and is doing so many things in his character that he did on Frasier.

348
00:37:43,120 --> 00:37:51,040
So it was fun for me. There were so many similarities. It was fun for me to watch and kind of in my head pretend that it was a younger version of that character or whatever.

349
00:37:51,040 --> 00:38:03,310
But anyway, I immediately tried to buy it and it's never been released on Blu -ray, let alone 4K and the DVD of it is like $25.

